<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence ยง 12:12<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I29fbc4d0630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>12.</label.designator><headtext>Burdens and Presumptions</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id72176b9682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>ยง </label.name><label.designator>12:12.</label.designator><headtext>Other presumptions</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The number of possible presumptions and inferences is almost <page no="444"/>unlimited. <eos/><bos/>In addition to marriage, some examples of other presumptions are those of sanity,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6ed24a07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] of intending the natural consequences of an act,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6ed24a17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] of continuance of a condition once shown to exist,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6ed24a27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>] of receipt of a letter properly deposited in the mail,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6ed4bb07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>] of knowledge of the law,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6ed4bb17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>] of the law of other states,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6ed4bb27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>] of the validity of official acts,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6ed4bb37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>] of innocence,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6ed4bb47fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">8</footnote.reference>] and of the identity of persons.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6ed4bb57fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">9</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The maxim res ipsa loquitur is sometimes thought of as a presumption, but it is really only an inference of fact that may be used by the jury.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6ed4bb67fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">10</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>There is no presumption of the order of death in a common disaster.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6ed72c07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">11</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>While there is a presumption that a person who owns or controls an automobile is in possession of contraband found therein, there is no reverse presumption with regard to a passenger in the automobile. <eos/><bos/>Thus, when police see the passenger of an automobile using contraband and the police retrieve this contraband after the passenger is told to leave the automobile, the defendant passenger is not entitled to a jury instruction <page no="445"/>regarding the presumption of ownership and control of an automobile or other property.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6ed72c17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">12</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>There is a presumption that children ordinarily belong in the care and custody of their parents.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6ed72c27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">13<page no="446"/></footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic6ed24a07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="1922105248" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I763c19827fc011ea988285db8533e975">Hinson v. State, 152 Ga. 243, 109 S.E. 661 (1921)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ed24a17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="1913020182" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I763c8eb27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Gaynor v. Travelers&apos; Ins. Co., 12 Ga. App. 601, 77 S.E. 1072 (1913)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ed24a27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="1938107071" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I763cdcd27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Clark v. Baker, 186 Ga. 65, 196 S.E. 750 (1938)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="1985134422" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I763cdcd57fc011ea988285db8533e975">Scott v. Jefferson, 174 Ga. App. 651, 331 S.E.2d 1 (1985)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="1986159429" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I763cdcd87fc011ea988285db8533e975">Howell v. State, 180 Ga. App. 749, 350 S.E.2d 473 (1986)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ed4bb07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="1904011573" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I763d52027fc011ea988285db8533e975">National Bldg. Ass&apos;n v. Quin, 120 Ga. 358, 47 S.E. 962 (1904)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="1983151892" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I763dc7327fc011ea988285db8533e975">Henson v. State, 168 Ga. App. 210, 308 S.E.2d 555 (1983)</cite.query>, the sender of a letter testified to the proper mailing of a letter and thus raised a presumption of delivery. <eos/><bos/>The addressee testified that he had never received the letter, so the presumption was entirely rebutted.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="1985126417" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I763e15527fc011ea988285db8533e975">Lyons Mfg. Co., Inc. v. Cedarbaum, 174 Ga. App. 218, 329 S.E.2d 559 (1985)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="1984148259" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I763e15557fc011ea988285db8533e975">Horton v. Allstate Ins. Co., 171 Ga. App. 707, 320 S.E.2d 761 (1984)</cite.query> (<case.history>overruled on other grounds by</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="1985132250" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I763e15587fc011ea988285db8533e975">Carter v. Banks, 254 Ga. 550, 330 S.E.2d 866 (1985)</cite.query>).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ed4bb17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="1854001912" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000359" ID="I763e8a817fc011ea988285db8533e975">Butler v. Livingston, 15 Ga. 565, 1854 WL 1663 (1854)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ed4bb27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="1871004103" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000359" ID="I763ed8a17fc011ea988285db8533e975">Hill v. Wilker, 41 Ga. 449, 1871 WL 2309 (1871)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ed4bb37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="1917018183" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I763f26c27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Beckham v. Gallemore, 147 Ga. 323, 93 S.E. 884 (1917)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ed4bb47fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="1922105372" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I763f9bf27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Connell v. State, 153 Ga. 151, 111 S.E. 545 (1922)</cite.query> (disapproved of <case.history>on other grounds by</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="1999244485" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I763f9bf57fc011ea988285db8533e975">Coleman v. State, 271 Ga. 800, 523 S.E.2d 852 (1999)</cite.query>).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ed4bb57fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="1874005576" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000359" ID="I764011217fc011ea988285db8533e975">Clark v. Pearson, 53 Ga. 496, 1874 WL 3119 (1874)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ed4bb67fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>10</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="1960123002" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I764086527fc011ea988285db8533e975">Macon Coca-Cola Bottling Co. v. Chancey, 101 Ga. App. 166, 112 S.E.2d 811 (1960)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="1963126573" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I764086557fc011ea988285db8533e975">Hayes v. Brown, 108 Ga. App. 360, 133 S.E.2d 102 (1963)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ed72c07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>11</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="1936106190" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I764122927fc011ea988285db8533e975">Pollard v. Gorman, 52 Ga. App. 127, 182 S.E. 678 (1935)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>In view of an old statutory provision, former GCA ยง 113-906 (not carried forward into the Code of 1981), none seemed to be needed. <eos/><bos/>The adoption of the Uniform Simultaneous Death Act, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-seq-number="00020" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST53-10-1" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I764122937fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. ยงยง 53-10-1 et seq.</cite.query>, did not make too great a change in the preexisting law.<eos/><page no="445"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ed72c17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>12</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="1991090161" w-seq-number="00021" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I7641bed27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Bell v. State, 198 Ga. App. 874, 403 S.E.2d 864 (1991)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6ed72c27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>13<page no="446"/></label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017244" w-serial-number="2048566034" w-seq-number="00022" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000999" ID="I764234017fc011ea988285db8533e975">Oni v. Oni, 2019 WL 2610356 (Ga. Ct. App. 2019)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="446"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. ยฉ 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE ยง 12:12<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
